<subSubSection id="2CB316984720FFBCF9B3F887FEA50AF4" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="641645134720FFBCF9B3F887FEA50AF4" blockId="20.[151,1436,1835,2016]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="56DD99014720FFBCF9B3F887FEF70A22" bold="true" box="[151,277,1835,1861]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Very little is known concerning this species. The whitish pronotum, grayish head, dark gray mesosternum, and yellow femora evidently distinguishes it from other known adults in Central America (
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24720FFBCF9BBF8D5FED80AF4" author="Traver, J. R." box="[159,314,1913,1939]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="491 - 503" refId="ref25402" refString="Traver, J. R. (1958) The subfamily Leptohyphinae (Ephemeroptera: Tricorythidae) Part I. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 51, 491 - 503." type="journal article" year="1958">Traver, 1958</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CB316984720FFBDF9E1F833FB380CA7" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="description">
<paragraph id="641645134720FFBDF9E1F833FB380CA7" blockId="20.[151,1436,1835,2016]" lastBlockId="21.[151,1436,152,912]" lastPageId="21" lastPageNumber="22" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<emphasis id="56DD99014720FFBCF9E1F833FE850ADE" bold="true" box="[197,359,1951,1977]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Description:</emphasis>
<emphasis id="56DD99014720FFBCF854F80CFE180ADE" box="[368,506,1952,1977]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Male Adult</emphasis>
: Length. Body, 4.0 mm; forewings, 4.0 mm; hind wings, 1.0 mm. General coloration: pronotum yellowish white, meso- and metanotum reddish-brown; abdomen yellowish-white with reddish brown. Head: dorsally grey, ventrally white; antennae white. Thorax: pronotum yellowish-white, shaded with pale grey, lateral margins with blackish shading; meso- and metanotum bright reddish-brown with grey shading medially and on pleura. Legs: femora yellowish; tibia and tarsus grayish-black. Forewing: membrane whitish; veins whitish, except C, Sc, and R grayish basally; no figure or description of the venation has been published. Hind wing: membrane pale; two longitudinal veins present. Abdomen. Segments two through six yellowish-white, basal and apical segments light reddish-brown; each nota with pale grey band medially. Genitalia: reported as the 
<taxonomicName id="A3A93E904721FFBDFB78FE2CFD2C0CFE" authorityName="Ulmer" authorityYear="1920" box="[604,718,384,409]" class="Insecta" family="Leptohyphidae" genus="Leptohyphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peterseni">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDFB78FE2CFD2C0CFE" box="[604,718,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">peterseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="BB12FBB14721FFBDFBFCFE2CFCEF0CFD" box="[728,781,384,410]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
(see “Discussion” below), which has forceps threesegmented, penes with basal half fused, distal parts divergent, “Y” shaped. 
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDFD2DFE0BFBAD0CA7" box="[1033,1103,423,448]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Larva</emphasis>
: Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CB316984721FFBDF9E1FE61FAE60C80" box="[197,1284,461,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="641645134721FFBDF9E1FE61FAE60C80" blockId="21.[151,1436,152,912]" box="[197,1284,461,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDF9E1FE61FEBC0C80" bold="true" box="[197,350,461,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Distribution</emphasis>
: Known from 
<collectingRegion id="A66D8BF14721FFBDFB2FFE61FD9A0C80" box="[523,632,461,487]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1CBE05834721FFBDFBA0FE61FD3F0C80" box="[644,733,461,487]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDFBC8FE61FC5D0C80" author="McCafferty, W. P." box="[748,959,461,487]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="9 - 11" refId="ref25154" refString="McCafferty, W. P. (1985) New records of Ephemeroptera from Middle America. International Quarterly of Entomology, 1, 9 - 11." type="journal article" year="1985">McCafferty, 1985</bibRefCitation>
) and Antimano, 
<collectingCountry id="1CBE05834721FFBDFDA0FE61FAE20C80" box="[1156,1280,461,487]" name="Venezuela" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CB316984721FFBDF9E1FE5FFD010E24" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="641645134721FFBDF9E1FE5FFD010E24" blockId="21.[151,1436,152,912]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDF9E1FE5FFEAB0F6A" bold="true" box="[197,329,499,525]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion</emphasis>
: Described by 
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDF8DDFE58FD790F69" author="Traver, J. R." box="[505,667,500,526]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="79 - 98" refId="ref25378" refString="Traver, J. R. (1943) New Venezuelan mayflies. Boletin de Entomologia Venezolana, 2, 79 - 98." type="journal article" year="1943">Traver (1943)</bibRefCitation>
from a single male subimago from Antimano, 
<collectingCountry id="1CBE05834721FFBDFD9BFE58FAD50F69" box="[1215,1335,500,526]" name="Venezuela" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Venezuela</collectingCountry>
(located near the capital, Caracas). The genitalia were described as the 
<taxonomicName id="A3A93E904721FFBDFABCFDB6FBE50F54" authorityName="Ulmer" authorityYear="1920" box="[920,1031,538,563]" class="Insecta" family="Leptohyphidae" genus="Leptohyphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peterseni">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDFABCFDB6FBE50F54" box="[920,1031,538,563]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">peterseni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="BB12FBB14721FFBDFD35FDB6FBA70F53" box="[1041,1093,538,564]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
(“Y” shaped, typical for all known male adults of the genus), but lost while being prepared for mounting. The sketch of the hind wing given by Traver (fig. 3, 
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDF8F3FDC4FD9D0FE5" author="Traver, J. R." box="[471,639,616,642]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="79 - 98" refId="ref25378" refString="Traver, J. R. (1943) New Venezuelan mayflies. Boletin de Entomologia Venezolana, 2, 79 - 98." type="journal article" year="1943">Traver, 1943</bibRefCitation>
) is also typical of male 
<taxonomicName id="A3A93E904721FFBDFAE7FDC4FB840FE6" authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1882" box="[963,1126,616,641]" class="Insecta" family="Leptohyphidae" genus="Leptohyphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDFAE7FDC4FB840FE6" box="[963,1126,616,641]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Leptohyphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The whitish pronotum distinguished it from other known adults in Central America (
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDFAA4FD22FBFD0FCF" author="Traver, J. R." box="[896,1055,654,680]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="491 - 503" refId="ref25402" refString="Traver, J. R. (1958) The subfamily Leptohyphinae (Ephemeroptera: Tricorythidae) Part I. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 51, 491 - 503." type="journal article" year="1958">Traver, 1958</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDFD11FD22FAF50FCF" author="McCafferty, W. P." box="[1077,1303,654,680]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="9 - 11" refId="ref25154" refString="McCafferty, W. P. (1985) New records of Ephemeroptera from Middle America. International Quarterly of Entomology, 1, 9 - 11." type="journal article" year="1985">McCafferty (1985)</bibRefCitation>
reported it from 
<collectingRegion id="A66D8BF14721FFBDF9FCFD19FEA70FA8" box="[216,325,693,719]" country="Mexico" name="Guerrero" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Guerrero</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="1CBE05834721FFBDF876FD19FE4D0FA8" box="[338,431,693,719]" name="Mexico" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, its only other documented record. 
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDFA70FD19FBF30FA8" author="Molineri, C." box="[852,1041,693,719]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="47 - 70" refId="ref25268" refString="Molineri, C. (2003) Revision of the South American species of Leptohyphes Eaton (Ephemeroptera: Leptohyphidae) with a key to the nymphs. Studies on Neotropical Fauna and Environment, 38, 47 - 70." type="journal article" year="2003">Molineri (2003)</bibRefCitation>
briefly mentioned this species in his revision of the South American 
<taxonomicName id="A3A93E904721FFBDFB70FD70FD0D0F92" authorityName="Eaton" authorityYear="1882" box="[596,751,732,757]" class="Insecta" family="Leptohyphidae" genus="Leptohyphes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Ephemeroptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="56DD99014721FFBDFB70FD70FD0D0F92" box="[596,751,732,757]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Leptohyphes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but did not attempt to diagnosis it from other species. Despite attempts to located the 
<typeStatus id="BB12FBB14721FFBDFB23FCAEFDDB0E7B" box="[519,569,770,796]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
specimen, it cannot currently be found. The brief description given above is taken from 
<bibRefCitation id="003838E24721FFBDF81DFC85FE120E24" author="Traver, J. R." box="[313,496,809,835]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="79 - 98" refId="ref25378" refString="Traver, J. R. (1943) New Venezuelan mayflies. Boletin de Entomologia Venezolana, 2, 79 - 98." type="journal article" year="1943">Traver’s (1943)</bibRefCitation>
original description.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
